 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=pickkpockket999>Pickk Pockket999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 146<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/12/03 9:09:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=26442.topic&index=47>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hardcore server??</span><hr size=1> I think that is the big difference. Playing hardcore is more about how far you can get than any other type of &quot;standard&quot;. If I got a character to lvl 55 and died fighting Yael in the hole I would consider that an acomlishment (hitting 55, not dying to Yael) and would be happy to then start a new character. Like in Diablo it would be neat if a list of the highest characters (alive or dead) was kept on the sony sight with a scoring system similar to the SZ points system (if it were PvP).<br>
<br>
There are two types of mindsets. One would be horrified at the thought of losing all that time and energy when they were so close to their destination (lvl 65 etc). Others would chuckle and roll up another character because for them the journey is the destination. Obviously one mindset caters to the hardcore server mentality and I would love to play amongst others that feel the same way.<br>
<br>
